section:
Overview
In GêBR, theSeismic Processing Flows are organized in greater unities, called Lines. Lines are organized in Projects. Flows are Seismic Processing Flows.
A Project is a set of Lines
A Line is a set of Flows
So that, before creating and executing Flows, It's necessary to create projects and lines. See in how to create a project and a line and in to see how to create a Flow.
GêBR uses a resource available by the machines you have access. The jobs are coordinated and distributed for all machines by GêBR-maestro (coordinator). These jobs are effectively executed by GêBR-daemon (server). Requests are sent to maestro by GêBR-client (local).
The GêBR interface is organized in tabs:
Projects and Lines : hierarchy: Flows in Lines and Lines in Projects;
Flows : creating and executing Flows;
Flow Editor : editing and executing a Flow;
Job Control : Visualization of results.
GêBR tabs
GêBR also has additional resources in menu bar, on the top of the window.
Actions
Preferences : User preferences;
Servers : Maestro's configurations, servers and group of servers;
Quit : quit GêBR.
Help
Help : GêBR's documentation;
Examples : examples of seismic processing;
About : GêBR's version
GêBR's menus bar
